    "created_at": "2018-02-07T22:04:01Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-02-07T22:05:24Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I don't think the yellow paper should have any theorems at all. It is a specification for client implementers, compiler writers and researchers. The point of a specification is not really to prove interesting theorems but to unambiguously specify behaviour, and formalism/math exists to avoid ambiguity. \r\n\r\nHere are some examples of formal specifications of VM-like things that have partially the same type of aim as what I think the yellow paper has (unambiguous reference for implementers and researchers)\r\n\r\n- https://softwarefoundations.cis.upenn.edu/draft/plf-current/Stlc.html - semantics (and type system) of the STLC\r\n- http://www.r6rs.org/final/html/r6rs/r6rs-Z-H-15.html#node_chap_A - formal semantics of R6RS\r\n- http://sml-family.org/sml97-defn.pdf - formal definition of standard ML\r\n- https://arxiv.org/pdf/1007.4446.pdf, definitions of some interpreters\r\n\r\nthe first three linked to above do not contain proofs, their main value is in definition. (For the last link there are some proofs, but the main value in the paper is in the definitions, not the proofs. It also leads to the question: what theorems do you think would be worth proving in the yellow paper?)",
